column168: During a routine inspection at check in at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a small amount of liquid was found leaking from the tailgate of the rolloff box. A turnbuckle was found to be missing from the tailgate and was replaced and tightened.  The cleaned up material was placed back into the box and it was then taken to the ten day storage yard without further incident.
column169: The driver stated that the box was not leaking when picked up at the customer's site and he did not notice the missing turnbuckle but everything was tight.  The driver was cautioned to conduct a more thorough pretrip inspection to insure all turnbuckles are in place.  The customer was notified to insure all liquids are removed from the waste material prior to loading.

column168: The load was loaded at the Univar facility and had travelled about 290 miles when the driver was alerted by another trucker that he had something leaking from the trailer. He exited I 94 and parked on the entrance ramp and contacted 911. Response was by Eau Claire County Sheriff, WI State Patrol, Hixton and Black River Falls Fire Departments, WI DNR and WI Regional Hazmat Response. Carrier contacted Bay West Environmental Services of St Paul MN for containment and cleanup.    Two persons were evacuated for about 2 hours from a home downhill and downwind as a precautionary measure. Bay West personnel removed the and placed the drum in an overpack container. The drum showed damage on the bottom from what appears to be a hit by a forklift. It appears that during transit, the damage caused a small crack to occur, thus releasing about 14 gallons of flammable liquid. It was estimated by the response and spill cleanup teams that only a small amount leaked out after the truck stopped.    Cleanup personnel from Bay West Environmental Services cleaned up the absorbents and all contaminated snow. Since the ground is frozen and snow covered, no material reached the soil.    No on site decontamination of the vehicle was deemed necessary. The load was delivered and Bay West Environmental was contracted to dispose of the contaminated snow and absorbent waste.
column169: Since this incident was caused by hidden damage to the container, it is difficult, as a carrier, to do anything to prevent this from occurring. As a carrier, we implemented our Spill Contingency Plan and are following through with providing information to the shipper as well as the WI Department of Natural Resources. We will continue the contact with WI DNR to insure there are no further measures necessary to prevent environmental damage.

column168: On February 5, 2014 at 02:00 hours personnel in the CSXT Erwin Yard detected an odor from PROX 61001, a loaded tank car of Sulfur.  The car was isolated and the shipper, BP Products North America Inc was notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014-02-05-00029.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release from the connection between the manway nozzle and the manway cover.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative.  A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the release secured; the car was released for transport.   NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 209

column168: On (07FEB2014, at 1009, personnel in the CSXT Yeoman Yard discovered GAMX9782, a residue tank car of LPG, leaking from dome area of car. The car was isolated and (Suburban Propane, Tampa Fire/HazMat,  and CHEMTREC were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2014-02-07-00091). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found leaks from around the threads of both liquid line plugs. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. SWS personnel discovered bubbles still appearing around the liquid valves during a "snoop" test and turned both liquid line valve handles 1/4 to 1/2 turn to close, removed, cleaned, retaped and replaced both plugs.(This was after the Tampa FD originally closed an unidentified valve). The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required?no    Cause Code:119  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0)=100

column168: I, John Vergis, while doing a joint inspection in our Brewster Yard with Tony Schnieder from the FRA, we found while a cut of cars was being switched, that this car has liquid product coming from the Protective Housing.  We stopped the switching operation and climbed on top of the car to investigate.  We determined that the pressure relief device was burping liquid Butane every time the car was moved.  I informed the crew and Yardmaster of the problem and then had the car set off to an isolated track so that the car could then be transloaded.  The shipper was notified and they had Rail Loading Services come out and transload the car into another rail car.

column168: A load of non-hazardous lead ingots was offered to JBH; our driver Thomas Pierce was told by the shipper the load was non-hazardous and was not offered placards.  The bills showed UN2794 on board and did not cite the battery exception under 49 CFR 173.159 e.  After the load picked up, the unit was involved in a non-preventable accident, hit by another vehicle; a post-crash inspection was conducted by law enforcement.  The inspection report listed violations for no placards displayed and stated the load did not qualify for the battery exception due to exposed terminals, poor packaging and poor securement.  The load was reworked, rebraced and re-powered by JBH.  Photos confirm the PD's assessment; the cargo was not properly braced by the shipper.  Given that the load did not meet the requirements of the exception, it was transported by JBH as an undeclared hazmat load.
column169: This isssue has been addressed with JBH management, sales, and the customer.  When I spoke to the customer, they did not seem to understand that the battery exception must be met and not just assumed; I provided them with the regulations, photos, etc and explained why this particular load did not meet the exception.  JBH voluntarily will not be booking any additional used battery or battery core loads with this shipper until the shipper has addressed these issues.

column168: ALTHOUGH THE ORIGINAL NRC REPORTING OF QUANTITY OF MATERIAL RELEASED IN THIS INCIDENT BY AIRGAS (48 TO 255 LBS) WAS BASED ON TRUCK SCALE WEIGHTS AT TWO DIFFERENT LOCATIONS. ADDITIONALLY, WE BELIEVE THAT ESSENTIALLY ALL OF THE LIQUID AND VAPOR WAS TRANSFERRED AT AIRGAS'S FACILITY, A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID DID REMAINED IN THE TRAILER AFTER THE LEAK WAS CORRECTED, AND THE TRAILER RETURNED TO STOCKTON. COMMERCIAL TRUCK SCALES (USED AT BOTH ENDS OF THIS SHIPMENT) ARE GENERALLY ONLY ACCURATE TO +/-100 LBS AT BEST.    DUE TO THE SCALE VARIANCES, PRODUCT RETENTION IN THE TANK AND OUR KNOWLEDGE OF THE MATERIAL AND VISUAL EXAMINATION OF THE RELIEF VALVES; OUR ESTIMATE IS CLOSER TO APPROXIMATELY 10-15 LBS OF AMMONIA RELEASED AS WE STILL HAD APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, WHEN THE TANK RETURNED TO STOCKTON DUE TO SWEAT LINES ON THE CARGO TANK WHEN IT ARRIVED IN STOCKTON. BOTH RELIEF VALVES WERE REMOVED FOR FURTHER TESTING AND NEW MARSHALL EXCELSIOR RELIEFS WERE INSTALLED ON THE CARGO TANK ON 2-13-14 AND LEAK TESTED ONCE INSTALLED. THE CARGO TANK WAS THEN RETURNED TO SERVICE.    A SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT WILL BE FILED ONCE THE RELIEF VALVES ARE LEAK RATE TESTED TO GET A MORE ACCURATE LOSS.
column169: WE HAVE ALREADY REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE VALVE AND THE SECOND ONE IN THE TRAILER WITH RELIEF VALVES FROM ANOTHER MANUFACTURER AND LEAK TESTED THE CARGO TANK AFTER INSTALLATION.    WE HAVE A DCE AS CONSULTANT TO LEAK TEST THE DEFECTIVE VALVES AND TO LOOK INTO THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE. DEPENDING ON HIS REPORT WE MAY INITIATE ADDITIONAL INSPECTION PROTOCOL FOR THESE TRAILERS.

column168: Tom was delivering to Herdrich #202 located at 10 North Main Street in Liberty, IN.  while unloading, he moved one of his hoses, he picked up on the hose and it split and started to leak out of the hose and tore in half.  Tom went back to his truck to shut off the valves.  He proceeded to block off the area and clean up the spill with oil dri that was available at the store.  He contacted the safety department and I went to inspect the spill site.  upon arrival, there was still a very strong gasoline smell.  I contacted the after hours number and spoke with Todd Allen in Canton.  Todd contacted Excel and Warren Fox dispatched a crew from SWS Environmental to come clean the site.  The spill site was approximately 75ft x 36 ft.  It was mostly cleaned already other than some places where it had impacted the snow piles and snow and ice on the ground.  The crew disposed of the contaminated snow and Ice, checked all three observation wells for the tanks (two were dry and one had approximately 3 gallons of gas mixed in with water) and disposed of contaminated product.  a bio media was then sprayed on the site to help with the smell and to finish the clean up.

column168: On February 3rd at 1900 hours personnel in the CSXT Maxwell Yard discovered UTLX213403, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acrylate, Stabilized emitting odor from top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sasol North America was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-0203-00176.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to the liquid line valve closure plug being less than tool tight.  In addition, product was found above the ball valve indicating that the liquid line valve may be defective.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Sasols representative Terry Dohrer at 281-588-3334.  Contractor personnel removed the closure plug, applied Teflon tape and re-installed the plug with a wrench to secure the release.  Due to the fact that this container may have a defective valve the tank car was placed in bad order status until the shipper obtains a One Time Movement Approval.  This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 120 - Liquid line/valve closure plug less than tool tight, valve closed.    5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: On February 4, 2014, a Liquid Cargo portable tank of UN2313 Beta Picoline was being prepared for transit, when personnel noticed a strong odor coming from the tank. The odor suggested that the tank was leaking, and as a precautionary measure, Liquid Cargo personnel decided to transfer the material into a new tank to ensure no product leaked onto the roadway during transit. While the transfer was being conducted, a 2 inch x 5 inch section of the hose burst due to a blockage in the line. Approximately 20 gallons of material released onto a 33' x 18' area of gravel parking lot and an environmental contractor was dispatched to the site immediately for impact assessment and initial response. Granular absorbents were applied to the released material in order to neutralize the area, and the impacted area was covered with a tarp until an excavation could be scheduled.

A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting an inbound BNSF train in the railyard reported entrained tank car UTLX 209585 with commodity bubbling from its vacuum relief valve (VRV) fitting. Intact shipper seal numbered 149767 was removed from the protective/valve housing cover during this inspection. UTLX 209585 was set-out from its train and carefully moved to isolation at the facility's repair track. On 2/14/2014, contract responders inspected UTLX 209585 and reported finding commodity bubbling at the threaded VRV fitting. UTLX 209585 was depressurized and the VRV was removed. During VRV removal, minor galling at the thread surface was reported and cross-threading allowed commodity to escape at the VRV orifice. The threaded area of the VRV was inspected and cleaned. The VRV was re-installed and tool tightened. The valve housing cover was closed and sealed with seal HMRI 00340. Response was concluded at 1330 hrs. CST, 2/14/2014 after no further commodity release at the VRV threaded fitting was observed.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Local train crew reported product leaking down sides of car. Inspection of car revealed product to be leaking from the A end pressure relief valve due to car being shell full.  The pressure relief valve was temporarily gagged which secured car from further leakage.  The shipper was contacted, and arrangements were made to reduce the load.  Approximately 30 minutes later, product began leaking from the B end pressure relief valve; valve was temporarily gagged to prevent further release.  Upon arrival of tank truck, approximately 4700 gallons of product was off loaded, car was gauged with approximately 20 inches of outage.  After car was determined to be safe for movement, it was released to continue onto destination.
column169: Determine the correct amount of outage car is to be loaded, to allow for temperature change and expansion while transportation.

column25: YOCUM OIL COMPANY OAKDALE BULK PLANT
column168: Driver was making a delivery to a 1000 gallon tank for a school. Tank had heavy snow pack and ice around and on top of tank. Driver put 500 or so gallons into tank. He stopped to check the gallons on the meter that he pumped into tank. Site gauge on tank stated it was at 650 gallons. Driver started to fill tank again listening for the auto shut float switch to shut off. Driver heard and felt fuel coming out of the vent. Shut pumping down. He quickly grabbed his spill containment absorbent pads and floor dry. Containment was limited to tank concrete pad. All snow, ice and fuel were removed from the tank pad area. Float valve shut off, overfill alarm failed. Driver did not positively identify how much fuel was in the tank when starting.
column169: Corrective actions: School maintenance contacted to give recommendations on how to maintain there tank, gauge, and alarms. Also keep area clear of heavy snow and ice. Driver/operator needs to be re-trained in proper filling procedures. Needs to be very aware of the amount of fuel in the tank at all times. Training in what the size of the tank is and having a positive gallon amount in tank before fueling.

column25: YOCUM OIL COMPANY RCE BULK FACILITY
column168: Employee was transferring Ethanol fuel from a transport truck tank to a temporary storage tank. His tank pocket was full so he shut down to change pockets. He needed to disconnect valve to change to another pocket in the tank. When he did that he did not check to see if his fuel line was fully empty. Fuel was discharging out of the line onto and into the containment pad and area. Employee checked discharge valve and we found to be partially open. Employee shut fully and discharge of fuel stopped. Containment was initiated within the concrete containment area. An outside clean up vacuum truck was called to assist in clean up. Clean up estimate time was 2 1/2 to 3 hours.
column169: It was found that all unloading personnel need addition training to be consistent and accurate in the process of unloading Ethanol into the temporary storage tank. It was found that employees need to check there work and connections before starting pump product and connecting and disconnecting hoses.

column168: At 1201 EST, Con-way Safety contacted third party vendor in regards to a tote transfer at Terminal XWB, 15 Tamarac Road, Wilkes-Barre, PA 18702. It was reported that the 350 gallon tote experienced a cargo related issue and released UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance to the dock floor. Vendor dispatched a network contractor to the site with an ETA~ 2.5 hours to complete the transfer and cleanup the released material.  There was a thumb nail size crack in the upper corner of the tote indicating the need for the transfer.  Failure discovered during unloading process.

A driver was delivering a rolloff box containing hazardous waste to the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  He had set the box down and was instructed to pick the box back up as he neglected to weigh it prior to setting down.  While loading the box back onto the truck, he did not use proper care and the contents shifted, sliding to the back and over the rear tailgate and under the tarp.  Approximately 1/2 gallon of the sludge material fell onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and shoveled the material back into the rolloff box along with a shovelful of dirt.  He then weighed the box and set it back down without further incident.
column169: The driver was cautioned to use better care when loading and unloading full rolloff boxes to avoid recurrence.

At 22:19 on 2/1/14 tank car ACFX200130 (crude oil load) was found to have a drip coming out of the bottom outlet valve in the KCS Laredo Yard in Laredo, TX. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.    Upon arrival, the responders accessed the tank car and noted the top operated bottom outlet valve was in the open position. The bottom outlet valve took one and one half (1 ) turns to close tight. The shipper had the bottom outlet valve handle sealed in the open position. Also, the bottom outlet secondary closure cap was not tool tight, taking approx. a half () turn. It was noted that the bottom outlet valve stem packing was not properly sealed/tight and was also leaking.     The responders closed the tank car appurtenances tool tight, verified securement of the tank car, and notified appropriate personnel that the tank car is ready to safely return back into transportation.    * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: At approximately 1: AM on 2/11/2014 it was reported that tank car GLNX 86162 (Alkynated Phenols Load {Rear End Grease for auto axles}) was leaking from above the B end trucks in the KCS Shreveport Yard in Shreveport, LA. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.  Once the tank car was isolated and secured emergency responders accessed the tank car to assess the leak. Upon further inspection it was noted that the source of the leak was a ~34 inch crack in the tank shell and gusset plates at the stub sill weld area. A containment pool was installed, and a small suction initiated on the tank car to slow down any leaks. The tank car required a field transfer of the lading.  Tank car UTLX 667874 was secured to be the receiving car for field transfer of lading. On 2/14/14 a transfer of the lading was completed, car was purged and cleaned and the inside condition of the car inspected.     * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.

Tank car GATX 47185 was reported dripping commodity off its side shell while at the railyard's repair track awaiting wheel inspection. A receptacle was placed under GATX 47185 to catch the ebbing commodity drips. Contract responders inspected GATX 47185 and reported the safety vent's 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured allowing commodity to escape at the disc's opening. Also, the Salco safety vent housing's 'quick inspect body' had damage near the top cap connection which required replacement. The responders replaced the ruptured frangible disc and the damaged safety vent. Absorbent material was applied to observed ground spillage areas and later collected for disposal. Other observed spillage was neutralized with an acetic acid/water solution. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Intact shipper seals ASH072704 and 072710 were replaced by seals HMRI00456, 00457 and 00458. Response was concluded by 1345 hrs. CST, 2/21/2014.

column168: This shipment was discovered at approximately 0300 on February 25, 2014 at DHL Express, 236 Wendell H Ford Blvd, Erlanger, KY 41018. When completing the online 5800.1 report, it did not recognize UN3481 Lithium Ion Batteries Contained in Equipment.  My only choice (to be able to continue) was UN3091. A vacuum box container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the designated Clean Harbors  disposal facility at Clive, UT. During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door seal of the vacuum box container leaking onto the trailer fender. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material and placed it back into the vacuum box, tightened the rear door which stopped the leak: a containment diaper was secured to the vacuum box as an added measure. The shipment continued on to the disposal destination.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors' Kimball, NE facility it was determined the vacuum box was leaking due to the presence of free liquid. In order to prevent a recurrence, the initial shipper has been notified of the improper preparation and presence of free liquids in a solid waste stream, the driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, this specific container was placed out of service pending an inspection of the door seal.

Norfolk Southern train Z4QG406 derailed 5 loaded cars of ethanol on Florida East Coast Track at the approach to the bridge over the St. Johns River.  One car, KLRX 30940, rolled on its side and began to leak product from the liquid line flange.  The other 4 cars, UTLX 205998, FHRX 30695, GATX 18404, and KLRX 30883 were derailed but upright, not leakingt.   Contractor was called to transfer a portion of the contents of the car (so that it could be picked up) and remediate the area where the ethanol spilled.  The Times Union building was evacuated as a precaution.

column168: NS Mechanical Dept. employee reported small leak from bottom of tank car TILX 193943.  Conway Mechanical Dept. applied absorbent and a contractor was called to respond.  Contractor found the bottom outlet valve handle with the retaining pin out and in the "open" position, with product leaking around the threads of the cap.  Contractor moved the handle to the closed position,pinned it, removed the cap, drained the material captured in the outlet nozzle into a bucket and checked the valve for integrity.  The contractor reported that the valve was holding product so the cap was replaced and tightened and the car was released to destination.

column168: On 19 FEB14, at 1440, personnel in the CSXT Valdosta Yard discovered GATX1628, a loaded tank car of CARBAMATE PESTICIDES leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and DuPont was notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2014-02-19-00196. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found loose plug and partially opened B-end liquid line valve. Contractor personnel closed the b-end liquid valve and tightened plug and inserted vapor line and a-end liquid line plugs which were also removed but not leaking, and decontaminated the car. Train A12 was meeting Train 182 when A12 reported a strong odor coming from the rear of Train 182.  Train 182 was stopped and contractor called to inspect.  Contractor found odor to be coming from tank car GATX 28786.  Upon examination the contractor found the manway had a deteriorated gasket.  Gasket was replaced, manway bolts tightened and car and train were released.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Veolia picked up (13) 55 gallon drums at Silver Eagle Refinery in Woods Cross, Utah. After securing the load, the driver proceeded to Veolia's 10 day in-transit  facility located in North Salt Lake, Utah (approximately 2 miles from the generators site where the drums were loaded). Upon arriving at the Veolia facility, the driver proceeded to off load the palletized drums using a pallet jack to remove the pallets from the truck and place them in the warehouse. The first pallet of drums was moved to the back of the truck and then when using the forklift one of the drums broke through the pallet, landing on the forklift rung, and hitting another drum which causing it to fall off the pallet. The drum fell approximatley 2 inches from the pallet to the floor of the truck. When the drum hit the floor of the truck, the lid opened just enough that the sludge started to leak out approximately 2 gallons. The driver overpacked the leaking drum and proceeded with the spill clean up. The driver notified the NRC because the release was over the RQ amount for the RCRA code K169, which is 10 lbs.
column169: Inspect all pallets to make sure they are in good condition and verify the drums are tightly secured to the pallet using straps or shrink wrap prior to loading them on the vehicle for transportation.

column168: On 02/03/14, a HOC Transport truck was offloading it's cargo of gasoline to the Speedway Gas Station in Bellville, OH.  While pumping fuel from the cargo tank to the gas station storage tank, the hose detached from the storage tank fitting, resulting in the release of approximately 300 gallons of gasoline to a 60' x 40' area of the asphalt parking area, a storm drain and a nearby 50' x 2' area of a culvert/ditch.  HOC contacted ERTS to manage the environmental clean-up response to this incident.  ERTS hired K&D Environmental to respond to the incident.  K&D personnel arrived to the site, applied absorbents, vacuumed out the storm drain, and performed a surface scrape on the ditch, removing the impacted soil.

On Friday February 14, 2014 Tank car TILX 260016 (load roofing tar, combustible liquid) was found leaking from the bottom appurtenances in the KCS Port Arthur Yard in Port Arthur, TX. No injuries reported. KCS employee made appropriate notifications and emergency responders activated.     Upon further inspection it was noted that the leak source was from a top-operated bottom outlet valve found slightly open, no gasket in place, and a bottom outlet cap less than tool tight. The responder contained the leaked lading, applied gasket to the bottom outlet cap, and tightened to tool tightness. However, the top operated bottom outlet valve would not close fully despite responder's closing efforts. This tank car appurtenance has been deemed defective and will require OTMA to home shop, clean and purge car, and repair defect.    * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector observed entrained tank car TILX 193029 with commodity on its side shell as it was departing the railyard on a BNSF train. Soon afterwards, this train was stopped on main track for further inspection of TILX 193029 by the FRA Inspector and a BNSF Trainmaster. This inspection revealed that the liquid valve's operating handle was in the full open position with this valve's closure plug not secure. The liquid valve operating handle was moved to its closed position and its closure plug secured which ended any further observed commodity release. At the next terminal, TILX 193029 was set-out of its train to enable cleaning of all spillage on its side shell.  TILX 193029 was cleaned with all valves and fittings re-inspected for proper securement on 2/16/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector observed and reported entrained tank car CBTX 735229 with commodity staining on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure. CBTX 735229 was carefully set-out from its train and isolated in the railyard for inspection. On 2/27/2014, contract responders inspecting CBTX 735229 reported finding one manway securement bolt/nut loose which was the leak cause. Inspection of the manway gasket condition revealed a small tear in the gasket and a new manway nozzle gasket was applied. The gasket tear did not appear to be a contributing factor of the manway closure leak. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Afterwards, the manway closure was properly secured and the spillage on CBTX 735229's side shell was cleaned. No ground impact from spillage was reported. Response was concluded by 1200 hrs. PST, 2/27/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

While beginning to load at the generators site using a double diaphram pump to help with the loading of the liquid into the vacuum tanker the two operators loading discovered a drain valve on the double diaphram pump was left open causing approximatly 15 gallons to leak onto concrete (no drains or waterways were effected). The operators contacted their manager and plant personell, contained the spill and cleaned up donning the proper personal protective equipment and packaged accordingly. New Jersey DEP was contacted (140219090112) the generator was satisfied with clean up and the tanker was loaded and transported the waste to the Clean Harbors Baltimore MD facility for disposal.
column169: A Management Investigation was performed and it was determined that the two Clean Harbors operators failed to secure the drain valve on the diaphram pump causing the spill. The local management team reviewed proper SOP while loading with the two operators and submitted an internal report.

column25: OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORPORATION C/O WESTWAY TERMINAL
column168: The driver arrived at the consignee and was shown where to unload. The driver connected his hoses to their storage tank, the receiver checked that the hoses were connected to the correct storage tank, and signed the driver's paperwork. The driver pressurized his cargo tank, began unloading, and the receiver left the area. Unknown to the driver there was an open valve on the storage tank and the entire load of 3,937 gallons was released into a contained area. The driver was unable to see anything as there were other tanks in the way and he couldn't hear anything because his compressor was running. The driver had completed unloading and was preparing to leave when the next shift noticed that the storage tank levels were not showing the product that was just unloaded. It was then that they discovered the open valve.
column169: Consignee personnel should insure that all valves on the storage tanks are closed before accepting delivery and remain with the driver during the unloading process.

column168: Brenntag Mid-South driver, Craig Jones delivered Isopropyl Alcohol 99% to Revlon in Oxford, NC. Upon arriving, Craig spoke to Phil Evans who signed off stating they could hold the load. Craig made sure Phil knew to watch the levels. After unloading the first 2 compartments, Craig again asked Phil to check the levels. Phil indicated he checked with an operator and the tank would hold the load. At the end of the delivery, Craig saw product spilling from the top of the tank. He cut the pump off and notified the customer. Phil told Craig the spill was not Brenntag's fault. We returned with a 1965 lb heel on the trailer. Approximately 25 gallons were released.
column169: The client site accepted responsibility for the tank overflow. The material was immediately cleaned up by Revlon personnel.  Revlon shipment receiving officials decided that smaller quantities of future loads (chemical liquid) will  be ordered and unloaded into their tanks to prevent liquid chemical being unloaded that are close the the capacity of the tank.

column168: Road driver Gordon domiciled in Chicago arrived Feb. 11 at 1931 to the Sheboygan terminal yard.  He parked his set in the yard and came in the building to punch in.  A local Sheboygan driver went out in the yard to split the set.  At that time he noticed the trailer 68966 was leaking fluid.  Trailer   68966 was a full exclusive use trailer load of 12 totes of Ethanol Solutions.  This trailer was loaded and sealed at the shipper location in KY.  The local ABF driver, Frank Schneider, called the branch manager at home to inform of the situation and find out what to do.  Frank was instructed to cal  l the ABF 1-800 Safety and Security hotline immediately.  He called the Safety line and they instructed him to control the spill from going into the street until a hazardous materials team could arrive.  SET Environmental Inc from Oak Creek, WI responded to the scene by 2230.  They assessed the situ  ation and cleaned up the spill by 0400 on Feb 12th.  Upon their arrival they broke the trailer seal #05642 and cut off the trailer lock.  They found the tote on the back of the trailer was the one leaking.  They emptied the remaining contents from the tote into two 55 gallon recovery drums.  Next th  ey cleaned up the ethanol that spilled on the ground and put that into 3 recovery drums.  The Haz Mat team broke the top seal on the tote but left the bottom seal intact.  They inspected the tote that leaked and came to the conclusion that the valve on the tote was faulty.  They inspected the surrou  nding streets to see if there was any contamination in the street but found none.  The only contamination was in the ABF yard.  All totes were transferred to another trailer and inspected for contamination.  The shipment was able to be offered for delivery on Feb. 12th.  The consignee recieved the e  mpty tote but did not accept the 2 drums of recovered material.
column169: ABF never touched the freight.  Since it was a faulty valve on the tote.  If possible shipper should check valves before filling with product.

column168: A drum of material was puncured by a forklift due to a faulty/broken pallet. The shipment was puncured near the bottom of the drum and the contents leaked out. A hazmat crew was called to clean the spill and and dilute the material to elimnate the smell. All residue was cleaned up.
column169: Discussed the importance of checking hazmat shipment before loading/unloading with dock personnel. Discussed hazmat cleanup and containment procedures. Folling up with appropriate terminals to ensure that they do not palletize the freight on broken skids.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. FACILITY OPERATOR FAILED TO PROPERLY INSPECT A 5,000 GALLON CARGO TANK TRAILER PRIOR TO TRANSFER FROM THE ON-SITE BULK TANK. THE CARGO TANK TRAILER ALREADY CONTAINED 4,500 GALLONS AND THE FACILITY OPERATOR SET THE AUTOMATED DELIVERY SYSTEM TO COMMENCE WITH A DELIVERY OF 4,400 GALLONS. DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS THE FACILITY OPERATOR NOTICED THAT THE TRAILER WAS OVERFLOWING AND SHUT DOWN THE TRANSFER. THE CARGO TANK LOADING AREA IS LOCATED WITHIN A PRIMARY CONTAINMENT AND CONSISTS OF AN IMPERMEABLE SURFACE. NO SOIL OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. HAWKINS, INC./VERTEX EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL PUMPED THE FREE LIQUIDS AND TRANSFERRED THE MATERIAL INTO THEIR RECLAMATION TANK FOR REUSE/TREATMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, HAWKINS, INC./VERTEX WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: A waste vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended Clean Harbors waste management facility. Upon stopping at the Clean Harbors Braintree MA facility the driver conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door of the vacuum box on his trailer. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a Clean Harbors response crew was dispatched to the scene where the response crew tighted the rear door which stopped the leak and added the spill material back into the vac box. The Mass DEP was notified (report 4-25014)Management discovered the product was mostly liquid as the shipping description dictated. It was decided to transfer the product to a Cusco (coded) vacuum tanker and transport to the disposal facility in two separate loads which was executed with no further incident.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors facility it was determined the vacuum box was leaking from the a comprimised gasket. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to review shipping descriptions and that vacuum boxes are prohibited to transport any liquids. The environmental consultant (TMC, 9 Basin Dr. Suite 190, Kearny NJ) who loaded the vacuum box with liquids at the generators site was also advised of the DOT regulations prohibiting liquids in vacuum boxes This specific container was placed out of service and sent back to the container's owner for repairs.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: Our driver removed the external valve at the request of the consignee, American Blending, to thaw frozen product in the delivery tube.  The internal valve was not completely closed off and as the product began to flow, there was no way to control or stop the flow.  The driver attempted to re-install the valve after the product began to flow with the help of an employee of the consignee.  Both were splattered with product before they were able to regain control of the product.  The spill was cleaned up in house by the consignee.
column169: Driver was warned about never taking off external valve while loaded.  This was against company policy and our driver has been retrained on proper unloading techniques.

column168: Import shipment (POE-Long Beach, CA) in 20 ft. Eurotainer ETNU 140853 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) after its arrival at the BNSF intermodal facility. ETNU 140853 was carefully removed from its railcar and isolated at the facility's containment area. No commodity was observed leaking during this time and no commodity residue was observed on its inbound intermodal railcar. Contract responders inspecting ETNU 140853 reported finding approx. 12 oz. of commodity liquid between ETNU 140853's closed external bottom outlet valve and its closure cap (dust cap). This commodity was absorbed and cleaned. Afterwards the BOV was monitored with no observed accumulation of commodity at the BOV. Teflon tape was applied to the threaded areas of the bottom outlet to ensure a good seal after the dust cap was re-secured. Response was concluded by 1640 hrs. CST 2/19/2014. Spent cleaning materials were earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE WORKING THE IRREG CHUTES SLID A HAZMAT PACKAGE ON ITS SIDE DOWN THE CHUTE AT DOOR 37 & ONTO THE IRREG BELT. HE NOTICED A PUDDLE OF PAINT FORMING AROUND PACKAGE SO HE STOPPED THE BELT & NOTIFIED THE NEAREST P/T SUPERVISOR. THE P/T SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I PUT CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT AROUND THE SPILL TO PREVENT IT FROM SPREADING. I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN PUT MORE ABSORBANT DOWN & BEGAN TO SOLIDIFY THE PAINT. I SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANT & PUT IT INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. BECAUSE THE BELT STILL APPEARED WET, I PUT SOME MORE ABSORBANT DOWN USED MY HAND BROOM TO CLEAN THE BELT OFF. I SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANT & ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT BOTH CANS WERE DENTED & THEIR LIDS HAD COME LOOSE.

column168: Driver lost control of his truck/trailer after moving to the side to avoid an oncoming car. The shoulder is very minimal in this area and his trailer got off the road, and he over-compensated trying to get back on the highway. This caused him to roll-over and slide across the road and ditch. The truck/trailer was on its side (passenger side) as it slid to a stop. Methanol was leaking out of the 2 rear wash out caps on the top of the trailer. They were both small streams. The driver was unconscious at the scene when emergency response arrived. Three Barton Solvents employees were sent to the scene shortly after the accident happened. They arrived at the scene about 2 hours later. We were able to stop the leaking caps by tightening them. The rest of the product on the trailer was pumped into another Barton trailer that arrived at the scene. Eagle Environmental was called in to handle the clean up. An estimate of 5-10 gallons of diesel fuel was spilled as well.

column168: Tank car TILX 193021 was reported to have an odor coming from the car while at the RIP track in Livonia, LA.  Inspection of the car found a small drip of product from the packing gland on the bottom outlet valve handle.  Both bolts securing the packing gland were tightened and the drip stopped.  The spilled material was remediated and the car released to continue in transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Train 14G/13 traveling East derailed 21 cars on Conemaugh Main in Vandergrift, PA.  Four tank cars of petroleum crude oil lost product.  UTLX 71033 lost an estimated 3,500 gallons due to a puncture, TILX 270185 lost an estimated 200 gal. from a sheared off vapor valve, TILX 254553 lost an estimated 800 gal due to the vapor and liquid valves being sheared off, and XTRX 156061 entered a building and lost an estimated 50 gal from a bottom outlet valve from which the nozzle had sheared and the handle partially actuated the valve.  The total estimated gal lost is 4,550 gal.  The other petroleum crude oil cars that were involved in the derailment, but did not release contents, were:  CBTX 729715 (rerailed), TILX 255044 (on side), XTRX 156039 (on side), TILX 270443 (on side), XTRX 156015 (on side), TCBX 254875 (on side), XTRX 156023 (on side), TILX 254800 (on side), CAPX 23604 (on side), TILX 255115 (on side), TILX 254311 (upright, 30 deg), TILX 255043 (upright, 30 deg), TILX 270363 (upright), TILX 270178 (on side), TILX 270378 (upright).  Tank cars PLMX 137509 (upside down) and AMOX 33712 (upright- rerailed), each containing loads of butane, also derailed and did not release contents.
column169: No additional comments.

NARA-ZS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE DEFECTS SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. column168: Attachment  Part VI - Description of Events and Package Failure    Lykins Transportation, Inc. I Incident Date:  February 3, 20 14    Our driver had loaded his transport at Marathon Petroleum  Co. LP facility at 40 IS River Rd. in Cincinnati and was enroot  to destination traveling EB on River Road (US Rt. 50) when driver of an automobile  lost control and crossed center  line striking our vehicle on drivers side tractor tandem  axles and down along left side of trailer.  Our driver attempted to veer right from oncoming car as he was struck.  The tractor of our tractor/trailer transport struck light pole, along side of roadway and from the impact of the other  car and the striking of the pole our trailer then flipped over onto the top rails of the trailer landing on roadway.  During this activity the fifth wheel mounting was separated from the tractor frame mounting area with the fifth wheel  plate remaining hooked  to the trailer.  During to rollover/flipping process the driver's side front compartment of trailer appears to have struck the rear frame rail of our tractor and a gouge/ripped  area in the barrel skin of the trailer resulted.   Fuel evacuated from the gouged area of the trailer front compartment onto the roadway.  Duration of spill lasted approximately  30 minutes.  The Cincinnati Fire Department responded  the accident scene and attempted to slow flow of product from gouge with  a mastic material as well as applied foam onto the fuel spillage area and attempted to cordon  off and contain the spill area.  We retained services of Environmental Services, Inc. to respond to site and effect containment  and clean up  of the fuel discharge areas.  OHIO  EPA responded  with representative, Bill Lohner, to site and he directed  clean-up activities, assessed situation with City of Cincinnati MSD for fuel that had entered into storm  water  drains and also inspected adjacent Ohio River for any possible fuel impact.   Our maintenance staff was brought in to effect the pumping out/transfer of the product that remained on the overturned trailer into another transport unit that we  had brought to site.  Wrecker company responded  with equipment  to right and transport our tractor trailer transport unit to storage  holding lot post the accident.  The primary remediation  of the spill was completed  and the roadway was re-opened around 7:45 am.  Environmental Enterprises,  Inc. remained on site to facilitate balance of remediation  activities for duration of the morning.
column169: Part VII- Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence    This incident was caused by actions of another vehicle when the driver lost control, crossed  the center  line of the roadway and struck our transport unit causing the crash and resultant rollover of our trailer and spillage that resulted when the trailer appeared  to strike the back frame rail of the tractor during the rollover.  The integrity of the trailer, other  than the gouged area, was maintained.  No leakage occurred  from and piping, valves, lids or alike of the trailer.  The gauge thickness of the trailer is the industry standard; and again was only compromised by the impact with the frame rail of the tractor during the rollover of the unit. Our driver reacted  and managed to avoid a complete head-on impact, but due to the impact of the other vehicle did strike and come to rest with our tractor against the utility pole and as noted above the tractor trailer became disengaged the trailer rolled/flipped over onto its top rails landing within I    foot of the rear of the tractor.        NOTE: Pictures are attached  showing alignment of the tractor  trailer unit post the impact as well as the gouged area of the front trailer compartment.

column168: A Dana/Suttles tanker trailer was involved in a multi vehicle accident on the I-20 bridge over the Mississippi River. The tractor behind the Dana/Suttles tanker struck the rear end of the tanker severing the main valve of the tanker. The tanker was carrying approximately 5500 gallons of UN2924 hazardous waste. It was approximated by emergency responders that the tanker was losing 20 gallons a minute. The release was flowing out onto the roadway then into a drain that discharged into the Mississippi River.

On Thursday 2/13/14, Quality Carriers came in to the TRANSFLO Columbus, OH terminal which is operated by Savage Services Corp, at 8:00am with trailer 70651 for a load of Xylene, order number 3501051957, going to PPG industries in Oak Creek Wisconsin.  Trailer 70651 was rejected by Sherry Ratliff due to an incorrect wash. Citgo was contacted and the driver (Manual Dunn) was sent out to get the correct wash.  Driver returned from Quala wash at 1:06pm, and he was sent to track three for loading. Operator Scott Yantes began setting up platform pump PLP1576 and verified the load. Mr. Yantes began transferring the Citgo Xylene (UN1307) from railcar GATX 50988 at approximately 1:45pm, when Operator Jared Davis noticed the product coming from the rear outlet valve. Mr. Davis immediately notified Scott, and at that time Mr. Yantes shut the pump down and noticed the rear cap on the trailer had come off. He quickly closed the valve and placed the cap back on the trailer.  Mr. Yantes and Mr. Davis immediately began containing the spill with absorbent and notified Ops Manager Don Driver about the spill. After containing the spill, it was determined approximately 20 gallons had spilled onto the asphalt. No storm drains or ballast were contacted during the release. In addition, there was no associated injury. Mr. Driver then contacted Randy Carter and John Donegan to report the release.  Mr. Driver then notified the US EPA region 5 spill response hotline, National Response Center and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency. Mr. Driver was given a reference number concerning the spill (1073887)  Terminal personnel cleaned up the area, placing the contaminated absorbent into trash cans then placing more absorbent down and bushing it into the asphalt to ensure they got all of the xylene. The terminal ended up with four cans of used absorbent, which will be disposed of in an appropriate matter.

column168: The internal and external valve appeared to be closed when the driver went to take the cap off the discharge valve on the cargo tank to hook up the discarge hose.  When he took the cap off, product ran out.  Driver immediately went to activate the emergency shut off valve on the cargo tank.  That slowed the flow enough to get the cap back on, but did not stop the spillage resulting in an approximate 25 gallon spill.  Spill went into a concrete containment area and was not released into the environment.   An emergency response team was called to clean up the spill and transfer the rest of the product into another trailer.
column169: When empty, the cargo tank was inspected to see why the internal and external valve both failed which is very unusual.  It was discovered that the tip of a power washing wand was lodged in the internal valve preventing it from fulling closing.  There was no indication what would have caused the external valve to fail unless something was also lodged in there and was dislodged during the spill.  The tankwash has been notified of the incident and will follow up with proper training.  The driver also did not follow proper procedure.  If he had opened the bleeder valve before he took the cap off, he would have known there was product in the cavity and would not have removed the cap. Driver is being coached on the use of the bleeder valve.

column168: On February 28, 2014, at 11:23 hours, a derailment occurred at the CSXT Stanley Yard, Walbridge, OH which impacted GATX 7963, a loaded tank car of UN2448, Molten Sulfur on an adjacent track. The tank car was inspected and various damage from the incident was found as well as sloshed product around the manway. The shipper, BP Products of North America, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-02-28-00131. Eagle Railcar, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Stanley Yard for damage assessment and inspection. Eagle Railcar found six of the six manway swing bolts less than tool tight and were tightened approximately three complete turns each. The shipper representative,was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and GATX 7963 will need to be transferred due to damage from the incident.    NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:200

column168: Entrained tank car TAEX 2387 was reported with commodity spillage on its side shell after its arrival in the railyard. BNSF and contract responders inspected TAEX 2387 and reported the leak source was at the liquid valve's bolted mounting flange connection. Responder's found one stud bolt nut at the flange connection not tool tight. The flange gasket was inspected and it was covered with commodity. A new flange gasket was applied and the liquid valve's flange connection secured. Spillage on TAEX 2387's side shell and at the valve housing area was wiped. A small area of ground impact from commodity dripping off the side of TAEX 2387 was excavated. All spent cleaning materials and excavated soils were placed into a disposal drum and earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: Vehicle was traveling west bound on state road 128 following another vehicle and an unknown rate of speed. Both vehicles were headed toward milestone 27, which is a lease road going north. The vehicle in front braked suddenly causing the second vehicle to swerve to the right side of the roadway and go into the bar ditch. Upon entering the bar ditch the driver of the vehicle lost control causing it to roll three quarters of a turn. As the vehicle entered the bar ditch the vehicle declined from its original level position causing an imbalance in the rear of the vehicle. The vehicle then went into an inclined position “jumping” the front of the vehicle up onto the turn-off road. This forward momentum caused the front of the vehicle to “bounce” causing the vehicle to overturn onto its left side then roll onto its roof then came to a resting position on its right side facing in a north east direction. The overall damage caused the manway on the top of the tanker to break causing the diesel fuel to leak.
column169: To mitigate the failure to maintain proper following distance and responding correctly to traffic conditions ahead the following recommendations/actions have been suggested to prevent future incidents. It has been suggested that the best CMV driving practice, driver should maintain a 6 second following distance. We also suggest remedial training to employees in the area.

column14: 8 MI. S OF DEERFIELD, KS ON EA
column168: THIS WAS A ONE VEHICLE ROLL-OVER CRASH INVOLVING A SINGLE DRIVE AXLE STRAIGHT TRUCK CONTAINING LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FRESH WATER. THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON A PAVED COUNTY ROAD THROUGH TWO CONSECUTIVE CURVES AND WAS WITHIN THE SECOND CURVE, WHEN THE DRIVE AXLE LOST TRACTION FROM THE ROADWAY, WHICH WAS LIGHTLY COVERED WITH SNOW AND ICE. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL WHEN THE TRUCK'S DRIVE AXLE SLID SIDEWAYS OFF THE ROADWAY AND DOWN A STEEP ROADSIDE DITCH CONSTRUCTED OF LOOSE SANDY MATERIAL. THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONE COMPLETE TIME COMING TO REST ON ITS WHEELS. DURING THE ROLL-OVER, THE PIPE AND PIPE FITTINGS ASSOCIATED WITH THE GROUP OF IBC TANKS' INLETS/OUTLETS SHEARED OFF RELEASING THE ENTIRE QUANTITY OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH.    THE IMMEDIATE AREA SURROUNDING THE SCENE OF THE ROLL-OVER WAS RESTRICTED FROM PUBLIC ACCESS BY THE DRIVER, LAW ENFORCEMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ULTIMATELY SECURED THE SCENE. ONCE THE SCENE WAS DECLARED SAFE, WITHIN HOURS A COUNTY ROAD CONSTRUCTION CREW BEGAN BUILDING A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM USING DIRT TO ABSORB ANY MATERIAL THE GROUND DID NOT ABSORB. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS CLEANED THE CONTAIMINATED AREA BY EXCAVATING THE SOIL FOR PROPER REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL.
column169: THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS ROLL-OVER CRASH IS AN EXPERIENCED DRIVER, WHO IS FAMILIAR WITH THE COUNTY ROAD HE WAS TRAVELING ON. HOWEVER, SNOWY WEATHER, ICY ROAD CONDITIONS AND TRAVELING AN UNSAFE SPEED FOR THE CONDITIONS WERE THE LEADING CAUSES THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE CRASH. THIS DRIVER HAS COMPLETED A COURSE IN HAZARDOUS WEATHER DRIVING, BUT HE WILL RECEIVE ADDITION REMEDIAL TRAINING IN RECOGNIZING AND REDUCTING THE RISK OF EXTREME WEATHER DRIVING THROUGH BETTER TRIP PLANNING. HE WILL LEARN TO MODIFY HIS DRIVING HABITS TO SAFETY DRIVE IN HAZARDOUS WEATHER CONDITIONS.

HOWEVER, SNOWY WEATHER, ICY ROAD CONDITIONS AND TRAVELING AN UNSAFE SPEED FOR THE CONDITIONS WERE THE LEADING CAUSES THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE CRASH. THIS DRIVER HAS COMPLETED A COURSE IN HAZARDOUS WEATHER DRIVING, BUT HE WILL RECEIVE ADDITION REMEDIAL TRAINING IN RECOGNIZING AND REDUCTING THE RISK OF EXTREME WEATHER DRIVING THROUGH BETTER TRIP PLANNING. HE WILL LEARN TO MODIFY HIS DRIVING HABITS TO SAFETY DRIVE IN HAZARDOUS WEATHER CONDITIONS.

column14: 8 MI. S OF DEERFIELD, KS ON EA
column168: THIS WAS A ONE VEHICLE ROLL-OVER CRASH INVOLVING A SINGLE DRIVE AXLE STRAIGHT TRUCK CONTAINING LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FRESH WATER. THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON A PAVED COUNTY ROAD THROUGH TWO CONSECUTIVE CURVES AND WAS WITHIN THE SECOND CURVE, WHEN THE DRIVE AXLE LOST TRACTION FROM THE ROADWAY, WHICH WAS LIGHTLY COVERED WITH SNOW AND ICE. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL WHEN THE TRUCK'S DRIVE AXLE SLID SIDEWAYS OFF THE ROADWAY AND DOWN A STEEP ROADSIDE DITCH CONSTRUCTED OF LOOSE SANDY MATERIAL. THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONE COMPLETE TIME COMING TO REST ON ITS WHEELS. DURING THE ROLL-OVER, THE PIPE AND PIPE FITTINGS ASSOCIATED WITH THE GROUP OF IBC TANKS' INLETS/OUTLETS SHEARED OFF RELEASING THE ENTIRE QUANTITY OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH.    THE IMMEDIATE AREA SURROUNDING THE SCENE OF THE ROLL-OVER WAS RESTRICTED FROM PUBLIC ACCESS BY THE DRIVER, LAW ENFORCEMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ULTIMATELY SECURED THE SCENE. ONCE THE SCENE WAS DECLARED SAFE, WITHIN HOURS A COUNTY ROAD CONSTRUCTION CREW BEGAN BUILDING A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM USING DIRT TO ABSORB ANY MATERIAL THE GROUND DID NOT ABSORB. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS CLEANED THE CONTAIMINATED AREA BY EXCAVATING THE SOIL FOR PROPER REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While at the Slay Transportation Co., Inc.(SLAY) facility, a leaking ISO-tank was discovered. Approximately 25 gallons of free product released from the ISO-tank and impacted the asphalt parking lot surface. SLAY personnel deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface. United States Environmental Services (USES) was dispatched to complete the cleanup and transfer the product. USES deployed additional absorbent material as needed. USES collected the spent absorbent material and placed into drums for disposal. USES off-loaded the product into a new ISO-tank provided by SLAY. USES will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Slay TransportationCo., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Hill to RR crossing was icy. Had to make a split second decision whether to try to stop, or try to make it across the RR crossing. Made the decision to try to make crossing. Road was icy, truck wheels spun and I did not clear the crossing. If I would have tried to stop, I feel I would have been killed. Train hit the very back of the truck, tank came off of truck, and started on fire. There was a small crack in tank by the fill pipe, tank burned for 4 to 5 days. Tank wasin such a location that it posed no threat to property or persons and was allowed to burn itself out.
column169: We are routing trucks differently to cross RR tracks. (eliminating the hill).

column168: Hose was hooked up from cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  When product started to flow, they noticed product leaking from the butterfly clamp on the QRB on the discharge valve of the trailer.  They attempted to tighten it to stop the leak and were unsuccessful.  They closed the internal and external valve planning to take the cargo tank in for service.  The customer tried to get the dripping to stop before going on the roadway and in the process, the assembly came apart completely.  The internal valve appeared to be closed but it wasn't and all attempts to close it failed.  Failure of both valves allows the contents of the trailer to empty to the diked concrete pad of the truck rack.  One plant employee received two small first degree chemical burns to the face and was treated onsite.  We brought in an emergency response team to clean up and dispose of the product.
column169: The driver took full responsibility for the external valve failure.  He failed to do a proper pretrip inspection to make sure it was assembled correctly before the trailer was loaded.  He has since received remedial training.  Upon inspection of the trailer after the incident, it was found that the internal valve was dislodged.  We have never had this happen before and do not know what would have caused it to become dislodged.  The trailer had been in regular service with no issues.  The only  possible conclusion is that something occurred during a tankwash that dislodged it.  We have since sent a training aid document to the tankwashes that we use.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While offloading heating oil at above location, an overflow occurred, which resulted in the loss of approximately 100 gallons of free product.  Product affected the asphalt surface within containment area, and snow/gravel adjacent to the lot.  Datom Products was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Datom Products used absorbent material to recover free product, and removed the contaminated snow from impacted area.  Site was secured pending excavation.  Pending excavation schedule, heating oil was detected within ditchline across the lot and within Lake Ariel.  Datom Products returned to the site, used absorbent pads to skim residual product and boomed the adjacent ditch to prevent migration. column168: On February 21, 2014, a Dupre Logistics truck was delivering a shipment of UN1307 liquid xylene to the unmanned Oxy Permian tank battery.  Dupre Logistics was acting as the carrier for material shipped by Univar to Oxy Permian.  The Dupre driver was pumping the material from the Dupre truck to an Oxy Permian tank, when the tank overflowed, releasing approximately 120 gallons of material into the concrete containment area below the tank.  The containment area is approximately 10 feet by 10 feet, and the material was approximately two inches deep.  Initial investigation revealed that the tank volume gauge was malfunctioning, and the gauge did not show that the tank was at capacity.  The Dupre driver terminated the transfer once the overflow was noticed.  No soils, storm drains or waterways were impacted by this release.    Nalco Champion, owners of the tank facility, had hired Bronco Services of Hobbs, NM to perform the clean-up and remediation.

column168: At 2:10 pm on February 12, 2014, a truck owned and operated by Usher Transport, Inc. was involved in the incident described in this report.  The truck was traveling south at the time.  The crash resulted in damage to the tanker shell and one compartment (Compartment 1) was damaged and lost its contents, reported to be 3,046 gallons.  Remediation efforts to date have included excavation and disposal of soil, removal and disposal of contaminated water and product, and collection and disposal of contaminated water and product using sorbent materials.  Initial response activities continued through February 15, 2014, and site visits were performed daily through February 28, 2014.  Remediation and monitoring at the site continue, and Usher's representatives are working with Ohio EPA to finalize remediation plans for the site.
column169: The incident will be reviewed by Usher Transport, Inc.’s safety department and prevention measures will be evaluated.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: ON MONDAY FEBRUARY 17, 2014 RAILROAD TANK CAR PROX 60033 WAS BEING LOADED WITH 99% SULFURIC ACID AT THE PVS CHEMCIAL SOLUTIONS FACILITY. STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE STATE THAT THE "LOADER" IS TO ATTEND AND MONITOR THE TANK CAR WHILE IT IS BEING FILLED AND CLOSE THE FILL VALVE WHEN THE SPECIFIED LEVEL IN THE TANK CAR IS REACHED. AS THE ACID LEVEL ROSE IN THE TANK CAR, THE "LOADER" STATED THAT HE COULD NOT SEE THE LEVEL AND LEFT THE TANK CAR LOADING PLATFORM TO GET A FLASHLIGHT. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TANK CAR, SULFURIC ACID WAS OVERFLOWING FROM THE TOP OF THE LOADING DOME. THE ACID CASCADED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR AND ONTO THE GROUND AROUND THE TANK CAR. THE OVERFLOW OCCURED FOR LESS THAN ONE MINUTE AND RELEASED AN ESTIMATED 75 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID. NO ONE WAS INJURED FROM THIS INCIDENT. THIS INCIDENT WAS NOT CAUSED BY A MECHANICAL OR EQUIPMENT FAILURE (SEE THE "NA" IN PART III QUESTION 25) BUT RATHER BY HUMAN ERROR.  A SPILL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO NEUTRALIZE AND PICKUP THE RELEASED ACID. THE DEBRIS FROM THIS RELEASE HAS BEEN TESTED AND CHARACTERIZED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: ALTHOUGH MANUAL TANK CAR LOADING HAS BEEN A COMMON PRACTICE HERE AT PVS FOR MANY YEARS, PVS IS PURSUING AN AUTOMATIC LOADING SYSTEM THAT DOES NOT RELY ON HUMAN INTERACTION.  HUMAN ERROR IS THE GREATEST PRIMARY CAUSE OF ACCIDENTS DURING LOADING AND UNLOADING.  THEREFORE, PVS IS DESIGNING A LOADING SYSTEM THAT WILL METER THE ACID INTO THE TANK CAR AND STOP ACID FLOW AT A PREDETERMINED VOLUME.  A SECONDARY PROBE WILL BE USED AS A BACK-UP TO THIS PROCESS IN THE EVENT OF A METER FAILURE.  WITH THIS SYSTEM INSTALLED, THE RISK OF A RECURRENCE IS GREATLY MINIMIZED.

column168: THIS INCIDENT HAPPENED AT THE BEGINNING OF THE SECOND RUN. THE DRIVER'S FIRST STOP WAS AT THE NEIGHBOR'S, #159 LAKE ROAD, FAR HILLS, NJ TO FILL THEIR 2000 GALLON HEATING OIL TANK. HE COULD NOT FIND THE FILL PIPE DUE TO FOURTEEN PLUS INCHES OF SNOW. HE CONTINUED ON TO #135 LAKE ROAD WHERE HE ENCOUNTERED ICE DIRECTLY ABOVE WHERE THE SMALL CREEK FLOWS UNDER THE DRIVEWAY.      THE FRONT TRUCK TRIES GOT UP ON PACKED SNOW AND ICE ON BOTH EDGES OF BOTH PLOWED SNOW BANKS. THE PAVED DRIVEWAY AT THIS POINT DROPS ALMOST STRAIGHT DOWN ON BOTH SIDES, NO GAURDRAILS NOR EDGE MARKERS. I FEEL THE DRIVER WAS GOING TOO SLOW SINCE THE TRUCK SLID LITERALLY TO THE RIGHT, OFF THE PAVEMENT AND OVER APPROXIMATELY THREE-QUARTERS WHERE A TREE HELD IT FROM GOING TOTALLY OVER.    WHEN I GOT A CALL FROM THE OFFICE AND WAS TOLD WHAT THE DRIVER ADVISED, I IMMEDIATELY SAID TO CALL SOMERSET HILLS TOWING AND ADVISE OF THE SITUATION AND I WANT THEM THERE NOW, AND ALSO TO CALL FAR HILLS POLICE. UPON MY ARRIVAL AND SEEING THE SITUATION, I CALLED SSG/BARCO AND REQUESTED A FULL RESPONSE AND THE VAC TRUCK.  AT THIS POINT I COULD SEE A DIESEL FUEL DRIP COMING FROM THE FUEL WATER SEPARATOR NEXT TO THE ENGINE DIESEL FUEL TANK AND WAS ABLE TO PUT A FIVE GALLON BUCKET UNDER TO CATCH TO DRIP. WE COULD NOT ACCESS THE PASSENGER SIDE TOOLBOX NOR INSIDE CAB FOR SORBENTS. I THEN CALLED OUR OFFICE TO HAVE SOMEONE LOAD OUR PICKUP WITH OUR SORBENTS AND BOOMS AND TRANSPORT TO THE SITE, AND TO LEAVE THE PLOW ON THE TRUCK SINCE THE DRIVEWAY WOULD HAVE TO BE WIDENED TO GET THE EQUIPMENT IN. DURING THIS TIME I HAD OUR OTHER TRUCK GO TO NEIGHBOR'S TO FIND THEIR OIL FILL TO EMPTY OUT SINCE WE NEEDED TO PUMP FROM ONE TRUCK TO ANOTHER AT SOME POINT.    ON OUR DELIVERY TRUCKS WE HAVE BOTTOM PUMP OFF OUTLETS. THE OUTLET WAS ACCESSIBLE, BUT WE COULD NOT DO THE PUMP OFF SAFELY UNTIL THE TRACK WAS CABLED BY WRECKERS.  AT THIS POINT THE OWNER OF SOMERSET HILLS TOWING, MIKE BESSASPARIS HAD CONCERNS THT HIS BIGGEST WRECKER MIGHT NOT BE ADEQUATE, AND HE WOULD LIKE TO ALSO CALL IN A FRIEND WHO HAD ONE WITH A ROTATOR BOOM. I AGREED SINCE THE LOAD WAS STILL INTACT AND WE WANTED TO KEEP THE TRUCK AND TANK WITH THE MINIMAL DAMAGE WHICH HAD ALREADY HAPPENED.    BOTH SOMERSET COUNTY HAZMAT AND NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE ON-SITE AND WE HAD A DISCUSSION ON HOW I WANTED TO PUMP OFF THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRUCK. I WANTED TO USE THE BOTTOM PUMP OFF, HOOK SSG/BARCO VAC TRUCK, PULL OUR DELIVERY HOSE ABOVE THE VAC TRUCK TO CREATE "AIR" AND BEGIN TO EMPTY, BUT IT WOULD FORCE BARCO TO MAKE TWO (2) TRIPS BACK TO OUR BULK PLANT (ABOUT TEN MINUTES AWAY).  THE ON-SITE NEW JERSEY D.E.P. SAID IT WOULD TAKE TOO LONG AND WANTED ME TO CALL IN "KEN'S MARINE SERVICE" FROM BAYONNE, NJ WHICH IS AN HOUR AWAY. I DID, AT THEIR REQUEST. WHILE WAITING I USED OUR PICKUP TO WIDEN THE DRIVE OF SNOW, THEN WE BROUGHT IN ANOTHER COMPANY TO SALT THE DRIVE.    THE ROTATOR BOOM WRECKER ARRIVED AND ONCE THE DRIVE WAS SALTED, THE ROTATOR
column169: #1 HAVE EVERY SMALL FUEL TRUCK HAVE BOTTOM PUMP OFF. IF I DID NOT THEN A HOLE WOULD HAVE OT BEEN CUT IN THE TANK.    #2 REFUSE TO GO IN DRIVEWAY'S NOT PROPERLY CLEARED.

column168: THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON FEB 16, 2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM ON MERRICK ROAD IN MASSAPEQUA N.Y., JUST WEST OF DOVER RD.    THE TRUCK WAS HEADING WEST ON MERRICK RD WHEN THE DRIVER HEARD A PING (NOT A BANG) LIKE MAYBE SOMETHING HIT THE TRUCK/ THE VEHICLE WAS STILL RUNNING AND TRAVELING ABOUT 30 MILES PER HOUR. THE DRIVER LOOKED IN THE REAR VIEW MIRROR AND SAW THE REAR OF THE TRUCK IN FLAMES. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE TRUCK IN THE MIDDLE LANE AWAY FROM TREES & POWER LINE. HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK. HE COULD HEAR AND SEE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE WAY WITHIN ABOUT THREE MINUTES. HE DID NOT KNOW WHAT CAUSED THE FIRE AND HE ALSO DID NOT KNOW WHO CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. HE HAD LEFT HIS PHONE IN THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND IT WAS RETURNED TO HIM BY A DOT OFFICER A FEW HOURS LATER.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF DIESEL AND GASOLINE FUEL FRO DELIVERY. IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT DRIVER TOOK A FREEWAY CURVE TO FAST, CAUSING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TO TURN OVER, THEN BURST INTO FLAMES. TRUCK AND TRAILER BURNED IN FIRE.
column169: THE ACTIONS THAT S & M TRANSPORT ARE TAKING TO PREVENT THIS RECURRENCE ARE:    1. DRIVER TRAINING WITH EMPHASIS ON ROLLOVER PREVENTING USING FMCSA ROLLOVER PREVENTION VIDEO.  2. DRIVER OBSERVATION PROGRAM, WHERE DRIVERS ARE RANDOMLY SELECTED ONCE A MONTH FOR UNANNOUNCED OBSERVATIONS. DRIVER VIOLATIONS ARE NOTED AND CORRECTED.  3. DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS ARE HELD QUARTERLY.

column168: When the local FRA HazMat Inspectors were doing a routine inspection of the cars in the Brewster Yard, they found that tank car UTLX 957097 was leaking from the vapor valve.  I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE was contacted by Inspector Anthony Schneider to come out and take a look at the car.  When I arrived, I found that the vapor valve handle was not closed tightly and that the valve plug was loose.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped and I then tightened the valve plug.  The car was then released for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

On 02-11-2014, ramp agents were loading/unloading the baggage bin when a strong odor was noted.  It was determined that the odor was coming from a passengers box which was traveling from Dallas to Phoenix, through San Antonio.  Upon further investigation, the box was found to contain an inmarked bottle of purple liquid, which had leaked.

The Customer's checked luggage arrived at T-Point to be transported to the aircraft.  Agents at T-Point detected an odor of alcohol coming from this piece.  Upon inspection, they discovered bottles of beer that had opened as well as a half-full bottle of vodka (40% abv).

Crew chief working flight out to JFK contacted CSM Robin Cooper since there was a smell in the forward belly of flight AA1508 to JFK.  When CSM Cooper arrived at the gate and entered the aircraft belly there was a strong smell.  CSM was able to located the bag since it was wet on the outside and had strong smell. The bag was removed from the belly and inside two 12oz. bottles of Lysol Liquid Concentrate were found of which one had leaked completely inside the bag.  The spill did not come in contact with the aircraft.
